---
// Project page: Algebra 1 Tutor. Static Astro shell; VerificationFlow renders as
// static HTML at build (no client directive, zero JS); TutorChatDemo, BalanceStepper,
// CheckMyAnswer and CurriculumMap hydrate on scroll (client:visible, deterministic
// initial render); the micro-viz (band, CTA, prev/next minis) is a client:only
// island. The "Inside the textbook" gallery uses coded mockups (no external images)
// so it stays self-contained — swap in real screenshots from the live textbook later.
import Page from '../../layouts/Page.astro';
import ProjectVizIsland from '../../components/viz/ProjectVizIsland.jsx';
import { VerificationFlow, BuildPipeline, BalanceStepper, TutorChatDemo, CheckMyAnswer, CurriculumMap } from '../../components/viz/algebra-1-tutor.jsx';
import { projects } from '../../data/portfolio.js';
import '../../styles/microviz.css';
import '../../styles/algebra-1-tutor.css';

const p = projects.find((x) => x.id === 'algebra-1-tutor');
const idx = projects.findIndex((x) => x.id === 'algebra-1-tutor');
const prev = projects[(idx - 1 + projects.length) % projects.length];
const next = projects[(idx + 1) % projects.length];
const TEXTBOOK = p.demo;

const methods = [
  { h: 'Ask before telling', p: 'Hints arrive as questions on a graduated ladder, so you do the thinking. The tutor only narrows the gap.' },
  { h: 'Reads the actual mistake', p: 'Misconception diagnosis looks at your specific wrong answer and repairs the cause, not a generic “try again.”' },
  { h: 'Concrete before symbols', p: 'Balance scales for equations, money for negatives, input-output machines for functions, then the notation.' },
  { h: 'Worked examples that fade', p: 'Backward-faded examples show the full solution, then hand you one more step each time until you own it.' },
  { h: 'Honest encouragement', p: 'Effort is acknowledged plainly and a wrong answer is never praised, so the feedback stays worth trusting.' },
  { h: 'Checks for transfer', p: 'Instead of “make sense?”, it asks you to apply the idea somewhere new, the real test of understanding.' },
];

const freeTier = [
  { h: 'Runs on Sonnet 4.6', p: 'Tuned for Claude’s free plan, so no subscription is needed to get a full one-on-one tutor.' },
  { h: 'Degrades gracefully', p: 'When code execution is off, it falls back cleanly instead of breaking mid-lesson.' },
  { h: 'Progress Cards', p: 'Copy-paste a Progress Card to resume exactly where you left off, even in a brand-new chat.' },
  { h: 'Start anywhere', p: 'Prerequisite-aware: begin at any unit and the tutor patches the gaps behind it.' },
];

// Structured tech stack rendered as labeled rows, matching the other project pages.
const stack = [
  { layer: 'Tutor', key: ['Claude Agent Skill'], rest: ['SKILL.md', 'per-unit references'], note: 'Sonnet 4.6 · free tier' },
  { layer: 'Verification', key: ['SymPy'], rest: ['Python', 'pytest'] },
  { layer: 'Content', key: ['curriculum.yaml'], rest: ['LaTeX / Unicode', 'SVG figures'], note: 'single source of truth' },
  { layer: 'Textbook', key: ['GitHub Pages'], rest: ['static HTML'] },
  { layer: 'CI/CD', key: ['CircleCI'], rest: [], note: 'answer accuracy + surface alignment, every push' },
  { layer: 'Licensing', key: ['MIT'], rest: ['CC BY-NC 4.0', 'CC0'], note: 'code · content · images' },
];
---
{/* No ogImage yet: this page ships coded mockups (no hero screenshot), so it
    uses the valid generic site OG card. TODO: once a tutor OG/hero image is
    captured (e.g. /portfolio/assets/a1-hero.png), pass ogImage to match siblings. */}
<Page
  title="Algebra 1 Tutor, Roger Winter"
  description={p.desc}
  canonical="https://rogerwinter.dev/projects/algebra-1-tutor"
  active=""
  ogType="article"
>
  {/* hero */}
  <header class="a1-hero">
    <div class="a1-band">
      <ProjectVizIsland id="algebra-1-tutor" client:only="react" />
      <div class="a1-scrim"></div>
      <div class="a1-status"><i></i> {p.status}</div>
      <div class="a1-titlewrap">
        <div class="a1-logo" aria-label="algebra">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 40 40" role="img">
            <text x="15" y="29" text-anchor="middle" font-family="'Syne', sans-serif" font-style="italic" font-weight="800" font-size="29" fill="currentColor">x</text>
            <text x="31" y="15" text-anchor="middle" font-family="'Syne', sans-serif" font-weight="800" font-size="15" fill="currentColor">2</text>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="a1-eyebrow">Project {p.n}</p>
          <h1 class="a1-title">Algebra 1 Tutor</h1>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="a1-intro">
      <p class="a1-tagline">{p.tagline}</p>
      <div class="a1-actions">
        <a class="tm-btn demo" href={TEXTBOOK} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open the textbook ↗</a>
        <a class="tm-btn ghost" href={p.repo} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Get the skill ↗</a>
        <a class="tm-btn ghost" href="/">← All projects</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  {/* lede */}
  <section class="a1-lede">
    <p>An AI tutor that teaches from a textbook has a quiet failure mode: the book says one thing, the tutor says another. Algebra 1 Tutor keeps one source of truth, and makes SymPy prove the math before anything ships.</p>
    <p><span class="hl">909 problems, 614 re-derived by SymPy on every push, zero failures.</span> The example you read in the book is the exact example Claude pulls up when you ask, because both are generated from the same file. And the whole thing runs on Claude's free tier.</p>
  </section>

  {/* tutor chat demo */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <div class="a1-split">
      <div>
        <p class="a1-kicker">The tutor</p>
        <h2 class="a1-h2">It asks before it tells</h2>
        <p class="a1-p">The skill turns Claude into a patient tutor with full knowledge of your textbook. It nudges with questions instead of answers, reads a photo of your handwritten work, and catches the specific slip behind a wrong answer, then verifies the fix.</p>
        <p class="a1-p">Watch a short session: a sign error on <span class="mono">8 − 2x = 14</span>, caught and repaired.</p>
      </div>
      <figure class="a1-figure">
        <TutorChatDemo client:visible />
        <figcaption class="a1-figcap">Illustrative session · the real tutor runs in Claude</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* pedagogy methods */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">Why it works</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Teaching methods, distilled from research</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">The tutor doesn’t improvise its style. Deep research into cited teaching methods was condensed into a single pedagogical approach, baked into the skill so every session follows what actually helps people learn.</p>
    <div class="a1-cells">
      {methods.map((m) => (
        <div class="a1-cell"><h3>{m.h}</h3><p>{m.p}</p></div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* concrete -> symbolic */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <div class="a1-split">
      <div>
        <p class="a1-kicker">Concrete first</p>
        <h2 class="a1-h2">From balance scales to symbols</h2>
        <p class="a1-p">Equations make sense before the notation does when you can see them. An equation is a balance: whatever you do to one side, you do to the other. Take the same amount off both pans and the unknown stands alone.</p>
        <p class="a1-p">Try it, and watch the symbols keep step with the picture.</p>
      </div>
      <figure class="a1-figure">
        <BalanceStepper client:visible />
        <figcaption class="a1-figcap">Concrete → symbolic · the same move on both sides</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* check my answer */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <div class="a1-split rev">
      <figure class="a1-figure">
        <CheckMyAnswer client:visible />
        <figcaption class="a1-figcap">Pick each step · the final answer is checked by SymPy</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <div>
        <p class="a1-kicker">Try it</p>
        <h2 class="a1-h2">Solve one, step by step</h2>
        <p class="a1-p">This is the loop the tutor runs, right on the page: choose the next move, get a pointed nudge when a step goes wrong, and finish at a verified answer. The sign on a negative coefficient is exactly where most people slip. See if it catches you.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* one source of truth */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">Verified</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">One source of truth, checked by SymPy</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">Every worked example is stored once as machine-readable data and re-derived with SymPy. The textbook, the tutor, and the study guides all draw from that same source, so they can’t silently drift apart.</p>
    <p class="a1-p">From that one source, the build generates parallel versions: the student-facing textbook and the tutor’s own copy, plus matching study and tutor guides. Every example carries a reference number, like <span class="mono">[5.2-EX3]</span>, so the example you read in the book is exactly the one Claude pulls up when you ask about it. The page and the tutor always agree.</p>
    <figure class="a1-figure wide">
      <div class="a1-figbox"><VerificationFlow /></div>
      <figcaption class="a1-figcap">curriculum.yaml → four surfaces → SymPy re-check → CircleCI gate</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p class="a1-p">The numbers behind it: <span class="hl">909 problems, 614 auto-verified by SymPy, zero failures</span>, enforced on every push. The conceptual answers SymPy can’t check are reviewed by hand, and CI also guards notation, figure accuracy, and byte-identical builds.</p>
  </section>

  {/* curriculum map */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">The course</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Thirteen units, start anywhere</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">Fifty-two lessons run from the language of algebra to a quadratics capstone, with a standalone statistics unit. Pick any unit below: because the tutor is prerequisite-aware, you don’t have to start at the beginning.</p>
    <CurriculumMap client:visible />
  </section>

  {/* built for the free tier */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">No paywall</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Built to run on free Claude</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">A good tutor shouldn’t cost anything. The whole experience is designed for Claude’s free tier, with the rough edges of a stateless, no-code-execution session engineered around rather than ignored.</p>
    <div class="a1-cells four">
      {freeTier.map((m) => (
        <div class="a1-cell"><h3>{m.h}</h3><p>{m.p}</p></div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* inside the textbook (coded mockups) */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">The textbook</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Inside the book</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">The free browser textbook mirrors the tutor exactly: worked examples with answer reveals, reference codes you can hand the tutor for targeted help, and figures that are computed and verified rather than hand-drawn.</p>
    <div class="a1-gallery">
      <div class="a1-shot">
        <div class="top"><span class="dots"><i></i><i></i><i></i></span><span class="url">realrogerwinter.github.io/algebra-1-tutor</span></div>
        <div class="frame a1-book">
          <p class="bk-unit">Unit 5 · Linear Functions &amp; Their Graphs</p>
          <h4 class="bk-h">Slope as a rate of change</h4>
          <div class="bk-ex">
            <p class="bk-q">Find the slope of the line through (1, 2) and (4, 11).</p>
            <p class="bk-work">m = (11 − 2) ÷ (4 − 1) = 9 ÷ 3 = <b>3</b></p>
            <div class="bk-foot"><span class="bk-reveal">Show answer ▾</span><span class="bk-code">[5.2-EX3]</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cap"><b>Worked examples</b>: answer reveals and reference codes for targeted help</div>
      </div>
      <div class="a1-shot">
        <div class="top"><span class="dots"><i></i><i></i><i></i></span><span class="url">realrogerwinter.github.io/algebra-1-tutor</span></div>
        <div class="frame a1-graph">
          {/* Grid: origin (96,96), 36px per x-unit, 24px per y-unit. Geometry is
              held to y = 2x − 1: intercept (0,−1)→(96,120), (1,1)→(132,72),
              segment (−0.5,−2)→(78,144) to (2,3)→(168,24). */}
          <svg viewBox="0 0 240 168" role="img" aria-label="A computed graph of the line y = 2x minus 1 on a labeled grid, through the points (0, minus 1) and (1, 1)">
            <g class="gr-grid">
              {[24, 60, 96, 132, 168, 204].map((x) => <line x1={x} y1="24" x2={x} y2="144" />)}
              {[24, 48, 72, 96, 120, 144].map((y) => <line x1="24" y1={y} x2="204" y2={y} />)}
            </g>
            <line class="gr-axis" x1="24" y1="96" x2="204" y2="96" />
            <line class="gr-axis" x1="96" y1="24" x2="96" y2="144" />
            <line class="gr-line" x1="78" y1="144" x2="168" y2="24" />
            <circle class="gr-pt" cx="96" cy="120" r="3.4" />
            <circle class="gr-pt" cx="132" cy="72" r="3.4" />
            <text class="gr-lbl" x="200" y="18">y = 2x − 1</text>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="cap"><b>Computed figures</b>: every graph is generated and verified, not drawn by hand</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* how it was made */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">How it was made</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Written by Claude, proven by SymPy</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">None of this is typed by hand. The course started as deep research into how algebra is taught and tutored, the cited methods behind the pedagogy. Claude Opus turned that research into a full textbook using custom skills built for generating and editing high-quality teaching content.</p>
    <figure class="a1-figure wide">
      <div class="a1-figbox"><BuildPipeline /></div>
      <figcaption class="a1-figcap">Research → generate (Opus) → validate (SymPy) → human review → visuals → publish</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p class="a1-p">Every example is validated by SymPy against the single source of truth, then put through thorough human testing, review, and editing. The visuals are generated too: Claude builds the rich HTML and interactive figures, and Nano Banana Pro (Google’s Gemini 3 Pro Image) draws the illustrative images.</p>
    <p class="a1-p">The whole textbook is <span class="hl">free and open source</span> under permissive licenses, and anyone can contribute. Fixes and new explanations run through the same loop (research, generate, validate against SymPy, review), so the bar holds whether a change comes from Claude or a contributor.</p>
  </section>

  {/* template angle */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">Open source</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">A template for the next tutor</h2>
    <p class="a1-p">The skill, the curriculum format, and the verification tooling are all open source under permissive licenses. The hard parts are reusable: a pedagogy encoded as a skill, examples locked to a verified source, and a CI gate that catches drift between surfaces. Fork it and point the same machinery at a different subject.</p>
  </section>

  {/* tech stack */}
  <section class="a1-sec">
    <p class="a1-kicker">Under the hood</p>
    <h2 class="a1-h2">Tech stack</h2>
    <dl class="a1-stack">
      {stack.map((r) => (
        <div class="a1-strow">
          <dt>{r.layer}</dt>
          <dd>
            {r.key.map((k) => <span class="a1-chip key">{k}</span>)}
            {r.rest.map((k) => <span class="a1-chip">{k}</span>)}
            {r.note && <span class="note">{r.note}</span>}
          </dd>
        </div>
      ))}
    </dl>
  </section>

  {/* CTA */}
  <section class="a1-cta">
    <div class="mvbg"><ProjectVizIsland id="algebra-1-tutor" client:only="react" /></div>
    <div class="inner">
      <div>
        <h2>Learn algebra, free</h2>
        <p>Open the textbook in a tab, or add the skill to Claude and start a session. No signup, no paywall.</p>
        <span class="url">realrogerwinter.github.io/algebra-1-tutor</span>
      </div>
      <a class="tm-btn demo big" href={TEXTBOOK} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open the textbook ↗</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* prev/next */}
  <nav class="a1-nav">
    <a class="a1-navcard prev" href={`/projects/${prev.id}`}>
      <div class="miniviz"><ProjectVizIsland id={prev.id} client:only="react" /></div>
      <div class="miniscrim"></div>
      <div class="lbl"><div class="dir">← Previous</div><div class="nm">{prev.name}</div></div>
    </a>
    <a class="a1-navcard next" href={`/projects/${next.id}`}>
      <div class="miniviz"><ProjectVizIsland id={next.id} client:only="react" /></div>
      <div class="miniscrim"></div>
      <div class="lbl"><div class="dir">Next →</div><div class="nm">{next.name}</div></div>
    </a>
  </nav>
</Page>
